      "title": "How clinical neurophysiology may contribute to the understanding of a psychiatric disease such as schizophrenia",
      "abstract": "Summary Introduction.— The increasing knowledge about anatomical structures and cellular processesunderlying psychiatric disorders may help bridge the gap between clinical manifestations andbasicphysiologicalprocesses.Accordingly,importantinsightshavebeenbroughttheselastyearsinto a main psychiatric affection, i.e. schizophrenia. Material and methods.— Here we reviewed and described, by comparison to healthy people,different physiological parameters —oculomotor measures, startle response, and cognitiveevent related potentials, which are altered in schizophrenia, in order to link these physiologicalparameters to dysfunctional cognitive processes and speciﬁc clinical symptoms. Results.— Schizophrenic patients displayed: (1) abnormalities in smooth pursuit eye move-ments and saccadic inhibition during antisaccade tasks that may stem from the same prefrontal‘‘inhibitory’’ cortical dysfunction; (2) deﬁcits in prepulse inhibition and facilitation suggest-ing disturbed attentional modulations, which seem also correlated to abnormal patterns ofprefrontal activation; and (3) decreased amplitude for cognitive ERP situated all along the con-tinuum of the information processing, suggesting that schizophrenia shows neurophysiologicaldeﬁcits since the level of the sensory cortex and not only disturbances involving associativecortices and limbic structures."
    }
